07712nam a22009015i 9781478012344DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019054733  a97814780123447 a10.1515/97814780123442doi  a(DE-B1597)552539  a(OCoLC)1198930647  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aLC3719b.I55 2020 4aLC3719b.I55 2020 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a371.829/9722300aIndigenous Textual Cultures :bReading and Writing in the Age of Global Empire /ced. by Tony Ballantyne, Angela Wanhalla, Lachy Paterson. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (367 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Indigenous Textual Cultures, the Politics of Difference, and the Dynamism of Practice -- tPart I. Archives & Debates -- tChapter One. Ka Waihona Palapala Mānaleo: Research in a Time of Plenty. Colonialism and the Hawaiian-Language Archives -- tChapter Two. Kanak Writings and Written Tradition in the Archive of New Caledonia's 1917 War -- tChapter Three. Māori Literacy Practices in Colonial New Zealand -- tPart II. Orality & Texts -- tChapter Four. "Don't Destroy the Writing": Time-and Space-Based Communication and the Colonial Strategy of Mimicry in Nineteenth-Century Salish-Missionary Relations on Canada's Pacific Coast -- tChapter Five. Talking Traditions: Orality, Ecology, and Spirituality in Mangaia's Textual Culture -- tChapter Six. Polynesian Family Manuscripts (Puta Tupuna) from the Society and Austral Islands: Interior History, Formal Logic, and Social Uses -- tPart III. Readers -- tChapter Seven. Print Media, the Swahili Language, and Textual Cultures in Twentieth-Century Tanzania, ca. 1923-1939 -- tChapter Eight. Going Off Script: Aboriginal Rejection and Repurposing of English Literacies -- tChapter Nine. "Read It, Don't Smoke It!": Developing and Maintaining Literacy in Papua New Guinea -- tPart IV. Writers -- tChapter Ten. Colonial Copyright, Customs, and Indigenous Textualities: Literary Authority and Textual Citizenship -- tChapter Eleven. He Pukapuka Tataku i ngā Mahi a Te Rauparaha Nui: Reading Te Rauparaha through Time -- tChapter Twelve. Writing and Beyond in Indigenous North America: The Occom Network -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs modern European empires expanded, written language was critical to articulations of imperial authority and justifications of conquest. For imperial administrators and thinkers, the non-literacy of "native" societies demonstrated their primitiveness and inability to change. Yet as the contributors to Indigenous Textual Cultures make clear through cases from the Pacific Islands, Australasia, North America, and Africa, indigenous communities were highly adaptive and created novel, dynamic literary practices that preserved indigenous knowledge traditions. The contributors illustrate how modern literacy operated alongside orality rather than replacing it. Reconstructing multiple traditions of indigenous literacy and textual production, the contributors focus attention on the often hidden, forgotten, neglected, and marginalized cultural innovators who read, wrote, and used texts in endlessly creative ways. This volume demonstrates how the work of these innovators played pivotal roles in reimagining indigenous epistemologies, challenging colonial domination, and envisioning radical new futures.Contributors. Noelani Arista, Tony Ballantyne, Alban Bensa, Keith Thor Carlson, Evelyn Ellerman, Isabel Hofmeyr, Emma Hunter, Arini Loader, Adrian Muckle, Lachy Paterson, Laura Rademaker, Michael Reilly, Bruno Saura, Ivy T. Schweitzer, Angela Wanhalla  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF tit